gomodel:SYNGO_3726  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Regulation of Ca++ stores in spines.\nAnd in turn regulation of morphological and functional spine plasticity.\n\"The mechanism through which SP may promote plasticity is indicated by the observations that STIM-1, the sensor of calcium concentration in stores, and Orai-1, the calcium-induced calcium entry channel, are colocalized with SP, in the same dendritic spines.\"\nComparison of WT and SP-KO mice.\nFigure 6. Ca++ transients in response to photolysis of caged glutamate are larger in synaptopodin-containing spines regardless of spine shape\n\n17/3/2017 Pim\nFig.1/2: SP-KO results in changed synaptic transmission\nFig.6: Ca++ transients in response to photolysis of caged glutamate are larger in synaptopodin-containing spines regardless of spine shape\nFig.7: intracellular Ca-stores are responsible\nFig.8/9: SER is involved since STIM1 and Orai1 move into spines.. Experimental description: Mice were obtained from a colony at the University of Freiburg (Deller et al., 2003), bred and raised at a local animal facility." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-9681-3318" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0269-0311" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-9880-1214" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0001-9377-7414" ;
        dc:date           "2018-06-05" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_3726" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

